{
  "text": "Putative risk factors for CDI in cattle include younger age and antibiotic use. [CITATION_1] found that veal calves aged 13-28 days were twice as likely to shed C. difficile than those aged 36-45 days (odds ratio 4.57 vs. 2.79). Elsewhere, calves reached a peak of C. difficile shedding by at least 14-18 days of age [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Antimicrobial use appears to be a common practice in veal production in Europe [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and United States [CITATION_6] . The use of multiple antimicrobials, or polymixin E, or a beta-lactam antimicrobial was highly associated with C. difficile shedding in veal calves (odds ratio 5.83) [CITATION_7] . Interestingly, [CITATION_8] in the United States demonstrated no association between C. difficile shedding by calves and housing type, however, this requires further investigation as production systems for veal calves vary immensely within and between countries.",
  "correct_citation": {
